[DONE] documented test 95/1 on amd64 + arm64 (qemu)

[TODO] BUG: (filter pred (cdr xs)) inside a recursive fn evaluates to
       blank/error after one or more iterations. Repro:
         (def f (xs)
           (if (no xs) (list)
               (cons (car xs) (f (filter (fn (x) (> x 3)) (cdr xs))))))
         (prn (f (list 5 1 6 2 7)))   ; prints nothing
       Same fn without filter (just (cdr xs)) works. Workaround in
       benchmark/sieve.alc uses iterative has-divisor? walk instead.
       Suspect refcount issue in filter or in the recursion+filter
       interaction.

[TODO] Reserved-name shadowing: lookup() checks reserved_symbol BEFORE
       env, so `(= time (ffi-fn ...))` doesn't take effect at top level
       (alcove's builtin time wins). Either flip lookup order or
       provide an explicit "shadow" form.

[TODO] FFI: support struct-by-value, varargs (printf), callbacks (qsort
       comparator). Each needs a libffi closure setup but no fundamental
       blocker.

[TODO] Compile lambda for closures (currently AST-only). Bytecode VM's
       gcache caches global resolutions per-bc; for closures the cache
       would be wrong if a captured var mutates. Either disable gcache
       for closures or change OP_LOAD_GLOBAL semantics for that case.

[DONE] OP_MOD bytecode op + JIT shape for (fn (a b) (is (mod a b) K))
       — divides? was running as AST because mod was an unrecognized
       builtin. Now: mod is one bytecode op; divides? compiles to 10
       bytes + JITs to ~70 bytes of native (idiv + cmovz). sieve raw
       17ms → 6ms.
[DONE] (any? pred list) and (all? pred list) builtins — walk in C
       with one vm_invoke_values per element. Useful when called
       outside recursive contexts; see TODO below for the bug that
       limits use inside.

[TODO] BUG: (do (fn-call) other) loses `other` in AST-eval mode when
       fn-call is anything but prn — the second expression silently
       doesn't run. Repro:
         (def f (i) (if (> i 3) i (do (any? (fn (d) (is d 0)) (list 1)) (f (+ i 1)))))
         (f 1)         ; → only iter 1, no recursion
       Or even simpler:
         (def g (x) x) (def f (i) (if (> i 3) i (do (g 5) (f (+ i 1)))))
         (f 1)         ; → also stops after iter 1
       NOT a do-only bug — same shape via (if cond (do ...) ...) or
       (if (some-call-with-inline-closure ...) X Y) where the inline
       closure captures the recursive fn's env. With a top-level helper
       wrapping the call, recursion proceeds. Suspect refcount issue
       in the AST evaluator's flow when an internal cmd creates a
       closure that captures the calling env. Workaround: extract the
       closure-creation into a top-level def. Documented impact: the
       sieve benchmark uses an explicit recursive is-prime-given
       instead of (any? (fn (d) ...) acc) for this reason.

